windpower_ts <- ts(windpower$wind_united_states, start = c(2001, 1), frequency = 12)

windpower$date <- as.Date(windpower$date, format="%y-%b")
Acf(windpower_ts)

plot(windpower_ts)

stl_decomp <- stl(windpower_ts, s.window = "periodic")
plot(stl_decomp)

#Moving Average
MA12 <- ma(windpower_ts,order=24)
MA12_forecast <- forecast(MA12, h=12)
## Warning in ets(object, lambda = lambda, biasadj = biasadj,
## allow.multiplicative.trend = allow.multiplicative.trend, : Missing values
## encountered. Using longest contiguous portion of time series
plot(MA12_forecast)

#This model is based on the average wind power production over the last 24 months, or 2 years. Based on this average, it predicts the wind power production will steadily increase over the next 12 months, or 1 year.

#Naive
naive_forecast <- naive(windpower_ts, 12)
plot(naive_forecast)

#This model takes the wind power production from the last year, and forecasts the same production for the next year. For example, it takes the production of Feburary 2023, and forecasts that same production for February 2024.

#ETS
ets <- ets(windpower_ts)
forecast_ets <- forecast.ets(ets, h=12)
plot(forecast_ets)

#Holt Winters
HW <- HoltWinters(windpower_ts)
HW_forecast <- forecast(HW, h=12)
plot(HW_forecast)

#One Plot
plot(windpower_ts)
lines(MA12_forecast$fitted, col="blue")
lines(naive_forecast$fitted, col="orange")
lines(forecast_ets$fitted, col="red")

#Accuracy
accuracy(naive_forecast)

#My best model is the moving average. The MAPE is the lowest of all my models at 0.3267159, which means the mean absolute percentage error of this forecast is only 0.327%. This percentage showing the amount of error being this low indicates a very accurate forecast. The naive forecast's MAPE is 12.81%, which is the highest MAPE of all my forecasts. The ETS forecast's MAPE was 8.98%, and the Holt Winters forecast's MAPE was 10.9%. These percentages indicate there is smaller error than the naive forecast, but they still have greater errors than the moving average forecast. Overall, the moving average has the lowest MAPE, meaning it has the smallest average error, making it the best model.
